**Version Used**: `'3.8.0-3.20458.6 (b446afd3)'. Language version: 9.0`

**Steps to Reproduce**:

The following types are similar. The second one is the generic version of the first one (with class constraint).

````c#
    public sealed class NonGeneric
    {
        public NonGeneric(string? value) => Value = value;

        [MemberNotNullWhen(returnValue: true, member: "Value")]
        public bool IsNotNull => Value != null;

        public string? Value { get; }
    }

    public sealed class Generic<T> where T : class
    {
        public Generic(T? value) => Value = value;

        [MemberNotNullWhen(returnValue: true, member: "Value")]
        public bool IsNotNull => Value != null;

        public T? Value { get; }
    }
````

In the case of the generic class, the `MemberNotNullWhen` seems ignored

````c#
            var demo = new NonGeneric("");
            if (demo.IsNotNull)
            {
                _ = demo.Value.Length; // Ok, no warning
            }

            var demo2 = new Generic<string>("");
            if (demo2.IsNotNull)
            {
                _ = demo2.Value.Length; // CS8602, but I think this is not expected
            }
````

**Expected Behavior**:

The compiler doesn't report CS8602 when using `demo2.Value.Length`

**Actual Behavior**:

The compiler reports CS8602 when using `demo2.Value.Length`

